# Preparing for the Afterlife

![Lesson image for Preparing for the Afterlife](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Book_of_the_Dead_of_Hunefer_cropped_1.jpg)

Tombs, texts, amulets, and rituals expressed hopes for an ordered life beyond death. Practices differed by wealth, period, and community.

Egyptian funerary practice was not simply a fear of death. It expressed a desire for continuity: the dead person’s name, body, relationships, food, and social identity could remain part of an ordered existence. Mummification, tomb equipment, offerings, amulets, and written spells formed a changing set of practices rather than one timeless ritual. The Book of the Dead was not one fixed book either; it was a collection of spells selected and arranged for particular people and periods.

The famous judgment scene associated with Hunefer shows the deceased approaching a divine tribunal. Images organize a moral and cosmic argument: the heart is weighed against a symbol of truth and balance, while gods, scribes, and protective figures give the scene structure. We should not treat the image as a literal map of one universally shared afterlife. Its details reflect a tradition, a commission, and a specific historical moment.

When studying funerary objects, ask both what the object says about belief and what it says about resources. A lavish tomb can reveal devotion, but also access to specialists, materials, labor, and political status.

> **Source and image note.** This lesson was prepared from [the linked research source](https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/557590). The image is a separate visual primary-source or historical illustration prompt; examine what it shows, what it leaves out, and who made or preserved it.

